			<h2><p style="text-align: center">CASE STUDY: SPAM EMAIL DETECTION & CLASSIFICATION</p></h2><br/>
				
			<p>
				<h4>I. Executive Summary & Business Context</h4>
				<font size="2">
				Spam messages expose users to phishing and fraud risks while degrading trust in communication platforms. This project focuses on building an automated email and SMS filtering pipeline to accurately classify messages as either legitimate ("Ham") or "Spam". The primary business challenge is balancing <b>recall</b> (catching as much spam as possible) with <b>precision</b> (ensuring legitimate, business-critical messages are not falsely blocked).
				</font>
			</p>
			<br/>

			<p>
				<h4>II. Data Overview & Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)</h4>
				<font size="2">
				<ul>
					<li><b>Dataset Size:</b> 5,572 email records curated from Kaggle.</li>
					<li><b>Data Quality:</b> The dataset contains zero missing values or "None" text entries in the target features.</li>
					<li><b>Class Imbalance:</b> The data is highly imbalanced, consisting of 86.59% (4,825 records) legitimate "ham" emails and only 13.41% spam emails.</li>
					<li><b>Text Characteristics:</b> EDA revealed that most legitimate messages are under 100 characters long, while spam messages are typically longer, peaking around 160 characters.</li>
				</ul>
				</font>
			</p>
			<br/>

			<p>
				<h4>III. Methodology & Technical Approach</h4>
				<font size="2">
				<b>Data Preprocessing:</b> Categorical text labels were converted into numerical binary formats (0 and 1). A <code>CountVectorizer</code> was used for Naive Bayes models to transform raw text into a numerical matrix based on word frequency. For the RNN, text sequences were tokenized and padded to a maximum sequence length.<br/><br/>
				<b>Model Architecture:</b><br/>
				1. <b>Multinomial Naive Bayes:</b> Utilizes word frequencies as features to classify messages.<br/>
				2. <b>Bernoulli Naive Bayes:</b> Uses binary features to evaluate whether specific words are present or absent.<br/>
				3. <b>Recurrent Neural Network (RNN):</b> A deep learning architecture with an Embedding Layer (100 dimensions), a SimpleRNN Layer (128 units), a Dropout Layer (0.3), and a Dense Layer with sigmoid activation for binary classification.
				</font>
			</p>
			<br/>

			<p>
				<h4>IV. Results & Model Comparison</h4>
				<font size="2">
				The dataset was split into an 80% training set and a 20% testing set. Here is how the models performed:
				<ul>
					<li><b>Multinomial Naive Bayes:</b> 98% Accuracy | 0.984 ROC-AUC | 0.99 Ham Recall | 0.93 Spam Recall | 0.95 Spam Precision. Acts as a strong, balanced baseline.</li>
					<li><b>Bernoulli Naive Bayes:</b> 98% Accuracy | 0.997 ROC-AUC | 1.00 Ham Recall | 0.87 Spam Recall | 0.98 Spam Precision. Acts as a "high strictness" filter (perfect on legitimate emails, but misses some spam).</li>
					<li><b>RNN Model:</b> 99% Accuracy | 0.991 ROC-AUC | 1.00 Ham Recall | 0.91 Spam Recall | 0.98 Spam Precision. Delivered the strongest overall performance, effectively minimizing false alarms while strongly protecting users.</li>
				</ul>
				</font>
			</p>
			<br/>

			<p>
				<h4>V. Recruiter Focus: Skills Demonstrated & Business Impact</h4>
				<font size="2">
				<b>Technical Competencies:</b> Python, Pandas, NumPy, Matplotlib, Seaborn, Scikit-Learn (CountVectorizer, LabelEncoder, MultinomialNB, BernoulliNB, ROC-AUC), TensorFlow/Keras (Sequential modeling, Tokenization, Sequence padding, Word Embeddings, RNN layers, Dropout regularization).<br/><br/>
				<b>Business Value:</b>
				<ul>
					<li><b>Customer Experience:</b> High precision ensures important customer communications are not accidentally routed to spam.</li>
					<li><b>Risk Mitigation:</b> High recall for spam actively shields users from phishing attempts and fraudulent attacks.</li>
					<li><b>Operational Efficiency:</b> Automated filtering pipelines drastically reduce the financial overhead associated with manual content moderation.</li>
				</ul>
				</font>
			</p>
